'''Oka Kofun''' (岡古墳) was a [[Square Kofun|square-shaped tumulus]] (Hōfun) located in [[Fujidera City]], Osaka Prefecture, specifically at 731-1 Fujidera 4-chome. Excavations revealed that it was an early kofun within the [[Furuichi Kofun Cluster]], but residential development led to its near-total destruction.

== Overview ==  

[[File:岡古墳出土 埴輪 船.JPG|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Boat-shaped Haniwa}}{{small|Exhibited at {{ill|AICEL Shura Hall|ja|アイセルシュラホール|1=AICEL Shura Hall|12=draft|12=draft}}, Fujidera City Lifelong Learning Center.}}]]  
The Oka Kofun was located east of the outer moat of {{ill|Okamisanzai Kofun|ja|岡ミサンザイ古墳|1=Okamisanzai Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}}, which is Historic Site1 as the tomb of {{ill|Emperor Chūai|ja|仲哀天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}. It was hypothesized to be a {{ill|baizuka|ja|陪塚|12=draft|12=draft}} (satellite mound) of this larger tumulus. Due to planned residential construction, excavations were conducted in 1980 by the Osaka Prefectural Board of Education and in 1981 by the Fujidera City Board of Education. The surveys revealed that the kofun was built in two tiers, measuring 34.5 meters in length and 5 meters in height at its base. burial goods such as blackened {{ill|cylindrical haniwa|ja|円筒埴輪|1=Cylindrical Haniwa|12=draft|12=draft}}, as well as house-shaped and boat-shaped haniwa, were unearthed.

== Internal burial and burial goods ==  

The internal structure included a {{ill|clay-coffin burial|ja|粘土槨|1=Clay coffin chamber|1=Clay coffin chamber|12=draft|12=draft}} that housed a {{ill|split-bamboo shaped wooden coffin|ja|割竹形木棺|1=Waritakegata Mokkan|12=draft|12=draft}}. A11roximately half of the clay coffin remained intact, measuring 2.5 meters in length and 1.88 meters in width. While the wooden coffin itself had decayed, impressions left in the clay coffin allowed researchers to determine its approximate type and size, confirming it as a split-bamboo shaped coffin with an external diameter of 80 centimeters. Within the coffin, three {{ill|bronze mirrors|ja|銅鏡|12=draft|12=draft}} were discovered. These mirrors, referred to as detypeed beast-shaped mirrors or quadruped mirrors, measured as follows:
1. Mirror 1: Diameter 12.6 cm  
2. Mirror 2: Diameter 11.9 cm  
3. Mirror 3: Diameter 11.5 cm  

== built ==  

Based on the blackened haniwa and other findings, the Oka Kofun was dated to the early typeation phase of the [[Furuichi Kofun Cluster]], contemporaneous with the {{ill|Tsudō Shiroyama Kofun|ja|津堂城山古墳|1=Tsudō-Shiroyama Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}}. The adjacent {{ill|Okamisanzai Kofun|ja|岡ミサンザイ古墳|1=Okamisanzai Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}} has been dated to the late 5th century or the end of the 5th century based on its haniwa, suggesting that the Oka Kofun was not a satellite mound of Oka Misanzai Kofun but an independent tumulus within the cluster.  

== References ==  

* Suezane Amano, ed. *"Oka Kofun - Investigation Report of the Furuichi Kofun Cluster Vol. 1 - Fujidera City Historic Site Survey Report No. 5"*, Fujidera City Board of Education, 1989.  

